    <!-- 1. STATIC VS DYNAMIC (Indigo) -->
    <section id="static-dynamic" class="card theme-indigo">
        <div class="card-header">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-table-columns"></i> Static vs Dynamic Data Structures
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-4">Data structures organize data for efficient access and manipulation. The main distinction is how memory is allocated.</p>

            <div class="table-responsive">
                <table>
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Feature</th>
                            <th>Static (e.g., Array)</th>
                            <th>Dynamic (e.g., List/ArrayList)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Size</strong></td>
                            <td>Fixed. Must be defined at creation.</td>
                            <td>Flexible. Grows/shrinks at runtime.</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Memory</strong></td>
                            <td>Contiguous (blocks next to each other).</td>
                            <td>Chained (can be scattered).</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Access</strong></td>
                            <td>Direct Access (via index).</td>
                            <td>Sometimes Sequential (depending on implementation).</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Pros</strong></td>
                            <td>Fast extraction, no overflow checks needed.</td>
                            <td>Memory efficient (no wasted space).</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <span class="tip-title"><i class="fa-solid fa-lightbulb"></i> Exam Tip</span>
                <p>Static structures risk <strong>Overflow</strong> (not enough space) or waste memory. Dynamic structures manage memory automatically but can be harder to implement from scratch.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. ARRAYS & LISTS (Cyan) -->
    <section id="lists-python" class="card theme-cyan">
        <div class="card-header">
            <i class="fa-brands fa-python"></i> Arrays & Lists (Python)
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-4">Python uses <strong>Lists</strong> which are dynamic arrays. They can hold mixed data types and resize automatically.</p>

            <div class="grid-2">
                <div>
                    <h3>1D Lists</h3>
                    <pre><code class="python"># Creation
grades = [70, 85, 90]
empty = []

# Methods
grades.append(60)     # Add to end
grades.insert(0, 50)  # Add at index 0
grades.remove(85)     # Remove by value
val = grades.pop()    # Remove & return last

# Access
print(grades[0])      # Direct access</code></pre>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3>2D Lists (Matrices)</h3>
                    <pre><code class="python"># 3x3 Grid of Zeros
matrix = [[0 for i in range(3)] 
             for j in range(3)]

# Access: list[row][col]
matrix[0][1] = 5  # Row 0, Col 1
val = matrix[2][2]

# Traversal
for row in range(3):
    for col in range(3):
        print(matrix[row][col])</code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <span class="tip-title"><i class="fa-solid fa-triangle-exclamation"></i> Common Mistake</span>
                <p>When creating 2D lists, avoid <code>[[0]*3]*3</code>. This creates references to the <em>same</em> internal list. Changing one row will change them all! Use list comprehension (as shown above) to create independent rows.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
