    <!-- 3. STACKS (Orange) -->
    <section id="stacks" class="card theme-orange">
        <div class="card-header">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-layer-group"></i> Stacks (LIFO Theory)
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-4">A <strong>Stack</strong> is an ephemeral data structure that works on the <strong>LIFO</strong> (Last In First Out) principle. Think of a stack of plates.</p>

            <div class="grid-2">
                <div>
                    <h3>Core Operations</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>push(item)</code>: Add item to the top.</li>
                        <li><code>pop()</code>: Remove and return the top item.</li>
                        <li><code>peek()</code>: View the top item without removing.</li>
                        <li><code>isEmpty()</code>: Check if stack has no items.</li>
                        <li><code>isFull()</code>: Check if stack reached limit (static only).</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3>Real-World Uses</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Undo button</strong>: Reverses most recent action.</li>
                        <li><strong>Browser Back button</strong>: LIFO history.</li>
                        <li><strong>Interrupt Handling</strong>: CPU saves current state to stack before handling interrupt.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Pseudocode Implementation</h3>
            <pre><code class="plaintext"># Push Operation
if isFull():
    print("Stack Overflow")
else:
    topPointer = topPointer + 1
    stack[topPointer] = newItem

# Pop Operation
if isEmpty():
    print("Stack Underflow")
else:
    item = stack[topPointer]
    topPointer = topPointer - 1
    return item</code></pre>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <span class="tip-title"><i class="fa-solid fa-lightbulb"></i> Stack Pointer</span>
                <p>The <strong>Stack Pointer</strong> always points to the top element (or the next free space, depending on implementation). If <code>topPointer == -1</code>, the stack is empty.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4. QUEUES (Pink) -->
    <section id="queues" class="card theme-pink">
        <div class="card-header">
            <i class="fa-solid fa-people-line"></i> Queues (FIFO Theory)
        </div>
        <div class="card-body">
            <p class="mb-4">A <strong>Queue</strong> works on the <strong>FIFO</strong> (First In First Out) principle. Think of a line at a supermarket.</p>

            <div class="grid-2">
                <div>
                    <h3>Core Operations</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><code>enqueue(item)</code>: Add item to the <strong>Rear</strong>.</li>
                        <li><code>dequeue()</code>: Remove item from the <strong>Front</strong>.</li>
                        <li><code>isEmpty()</code>: Check if number of items is 0.</li>
                        <li><code>isFull()</code>: Check if queue is at capacity.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div>
                    <h3>Real-World Uses</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Printer Queue</strong>: Documents printed in order sent.</li>
                        <li><strong>Keyboard Buffer</strong>: Characters appear in order typed.</li>
                        <li><strong>Process Scheduling</strong>: CPU handles tasks in order.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Pseudocode Implementation</h3>
            <pre><code class="plaintext"># Enqueue (Linear)
if isFull():
    error("Queue Full")
else:
    rearPointer = rearPointer + 1
    queue[rearPointer] = newItem

# Dequeue (Linear)
if isEmpty():
    error("Queue Empty")
else:
    item = queue[frontPointer]
    frontPointer = frontPointer + 1
    return item</code></pre>

            <div class="tip-box">
                <span class="tip-title"><i class="fa-solid fa-arrows-spin"></i> The Circular Queue</span>
                <p>In a linear queue, dequeueing leaves wasted space at the front. A <strong>Circular Queue</strong> wraps the pointers around: when the rear reaches the end, it goes back to the start (index 0) if there is space.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

